# File: tests/features/dom-tree-positional-root.feature
#
# Generated from: specs/bug-fix-dom-tree-add-positional-root-argument-consistent-with-other-dom-subcommands/requirements.md
# Issue: #251
# Type: Defect regression

@regression
Feature: dom tree accepts a positional ROOT argument
  The `dom tree` subcommand previously rejected positional target arguments
  (`agentchrome dom tree css:table` → "unexpected argument"), diverging from
  every sibling `dom` subcommand. This was fixed by adding an optional
  positional `ROOT` to `DomTreeArgs` that shares semantics with `--root` and
  conflicts with it via clap's `conflicts_with`.

  Background:
    Given a headless Chrome instance is connected
    And the browser is navigated to a fixture page containing a <table> element

  # --- Bug Is Fixed ---

  @regression
  Scenario: AC1 — positional ROOT is accepted
    When the user runs "agentchrome dom tree css:table --depth 3"
    Then the command exits with code 0
    And stdout contains a DOM tree rooted at a <table> element
    And the tree traversal is limited to depth 3

  # --- Related Behavior Still Works ---

  @regression
  Scenario: AC2 — --root flag still works
    When the user runs "agentchrome dom tree --root css:table --depth 3"
    Then the command exits with code 0
    And stdout is identical to the output of "agentchrome dom tree css:table --depth 3"

  @regression
  Scenario: AC3 — no-argument form prints the full document tree
    When the user runs "agentchrome dom tree"
    Then the command exits with code 0
    And stdout contains a DOM tree rooted at the document node

  # --- Conflict Handling ---

  @regression
  Scenario: AC4 — positional and --root together produce a conflict error
    When the user runs "agentchrome dom tree css:table --root css:div"
    Then the command exits with a non-zero code
    And stderr contains a clap conflict error mentioning "--root"

  # --- Help Text ---

  @regression
  Scenario: AC5 — help text advertises the positional
    When the user runs "agentchrome dom tree --help"
    Then the command exits with code 0
    And stdout contains "[ROOT]" in the usage line
    And stdout contains an EXAMPLES entry that invokes "dom tree" with a positional target
